{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:21:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:21:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"776"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/776"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.07,0.13,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/776"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11063"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45054"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a four-month history of painless swelling in her left breast. The lump appears to vary in size during her menstrual cycle and there is no associated nipple discharge, recent breast trauma or fever. On examination she appears well. Breast examination shows a firm and smooth spherical 2 cm lump in the upper and outer quadrant of the breast. She is otherwise well and does not take any regular medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cyst","Ductal carcinoma in situ","Intraductal papilloma","Fat necrosis","Galactocele"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst any of the conditions listed could present as a lump in the breast, the commonest and most likely cause is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyst. \u003C/strong\u003ECyst is a common cause of breast lump in pre-menopausal women. It usually presents as a firm localised swelling that is smooth and well demarcated. The size usually varies according to the patient\u0027s menstrual cycle. To confirm the diagnosis, ultrasound and breast aspiration should be done.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E is another possible cause of benign breast lesion in pre-menopausal woman. However it usually presents with nipple discharge, which makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal carcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E is a less likely diagnosis as patients with DCIS usually presents with a painless firm mass which does not fluctuate during menstrual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFat necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E usually occurs following a history of trauma. Characteristic findings of fat necrosis includes a firm, irregular mass which does not fluctuate during menstrual cycle. It is also common for patients to present with skin changes, or nipple retraction due to the fibrotic tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of breast lump in lactating women. It is highly unlikely for galactocele to occur in non-lactating women.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Breast cyst clinically presents as a painless, smooth, firm lump which fluctuates during menstrual cycle.","Cyst is a common cause of benign breast lump in premenopausal women."],"references":["Kowalski A, Okoye E. Breast Cyst. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562196/","Morrow M. The evaluation of common breast problems. Am fam physician. 2000;61(8):2371. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2000/0415/p2371.html","Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions. Part 2--breast lumps and lesions. Aust Fam Physician. 2005;34(4):253-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15861746/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"776"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-07T16:07:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:45:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42337"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"